ews|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/30/fashion/brian-ellner-a-gay-rights-power-player-with-many-contacts.html|title=Brian Ellner, a Political Power Player, With Many Contacts|first=Jan|last=Hoffman|date=June 29, 2011|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n* [[Brian Anderson (skateboarder)|Brian Anderson]] \u2013 [[skateboard]]er<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/skateboarder-brian-anderson-gay_n_57eae21ae4b0c2407cda49ff|title=Professional Skateboarding Icon Brian Anderson Comes Out As Gay|first=Curtis M.|last=Wong|date=September 29, 2016|via=Huff Post}}</ref>\n\n===Visual arts===\n* [[Cass Bird]] \u2013 photographer and artist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/mothers-day-liya-kebede-georgina-chapman-make-a-difference|title=These Amazing Mothers Are Changing the World|first=Cond\u00e9|last=Nast|website=Glamour}}</ref>\n* [[Andrew Bolton (curator)|Andrew Bolton]] \u2013 head curator, the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]'s [[Costume Institute at The Met|Costume Institute]]<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* [[Anthony Goicolea]] \u2013 [[visual arts|artist]] chosen in June 2017 to design the official New York State LGBT monument<ref name=NYSOfficialLGBTMonument>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/25/arts/design/a-monument-to-gay-and-trangender-people-is-coming-to-new-york.html|title=A Winning Design for a New York Monument to Gay and Transgender People|author=Joshua Barone|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 25, 2017|accessdate=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Keith Haring]] \u2013 late artist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tate.org.uk/art/art-terms/g/graffiti-art/lists/five-things-know-keith-haring|title=Five Things to Know: Keith Haring \u2013 List|website=Tate Etc.}}</ref>\n* [[Annie Leibovitz]] \u2013 photographer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Love-family-celebrity-grief-Leibovitz-puts-2548168.php|title=Love, family, celebrity, grief \u2013 Leibovitz puts her life on display in photo memoir|first=Edward|last=Guthmann|date=November 1, 2006|website=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>\n* [[Robert Mapplethorpe]] \u2013 late photographer<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.out.com/art-books/2016/3/25/patti-smith-robert-mapplethorpe-he-was-picasso-you-couldnt-get-attached-anything|title=Patti Smith on Robert Mapplethorpe: 'He Was Like Picasso, You Couldn't Get Attached to Anything'|date=March 25, 2016|website=out.com}}</ref>\n* [[Todd Oldham]] \u2013 designer<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.askmen.com/celebs/men/business_politics/todd-oldham/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110409192639/http://www.askmen.com/celebs/men/business_politics/todd-oldham/|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 9, 2011|title=Todd Oldham Sports Biography, Photos & Rise To Success \u2013 AskMen|date=April 9, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Carter Smith]] \u2013 fashion photographer<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.out.com/out-exclusives/tastemakers/2014/09/10/filmmaker-carter-smith|title=Tastemakers 2014: Filmmaker Carter Smith explains how sexuality affects how you see the world|date=September 10, 2014|website=out.com}}</ref>\n* [[Andy Warhol]] \u2013 late artist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.warhol.org/lgbtq/|title=LGBTQ+|website=The Andy Warhol Museum}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Heritage of Pride]]\n* [[LGBT culture in New York City]]\n* [[LGBT history in New York]]\n* [[LGBT rights in New York]]\n* [[Same-sex marriage in New York]]\n* [[Stonewall riots]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=George Chauncey|title=Gay New York: Gender, Urban Culture, and the Making of the Gay Male World, 1890\u20131940|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TCLLBQAAQBAJ&pg=PP1|year=2008|publisher=Basic Books|isbn=978-0-7867-2335-5}}\n*{{cite book|author=Charles Kaiser|title=The Gay Metropolis: The Landmark History of Gay Life in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HO7IKU79zgAC&pg=PP1|year=2007|publisher=Grove Press|isbn=978-0-8021-4317-4}}\n{{LGBT in New York}}\n{{LGBT}}\n{{LGBT Americans by location}}\n{{Sexual revolution}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT culture in New York City|*]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Lists of LGBT-related people]]\n[[Category:Lists of people from New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Multiple image\n|header='''''LGBTQ culture in New York City'''''|width=275\n|image1=Stonewall_Inn_5_pride_weekend_2016.jpg|\n|caption1=The [[Stonewall Inn]] in the [[gay village]] of [[Greenwich Village]], [[Manhattan]], the cradle of the modern [[gay rights]] movement.<ref name=GayGreenwichVillage1>{{cite web|url=https://theculturetrip.com/north-america/usa/new-york/articles/why-new-york-city-is-a-major-destination-for-lgbt-travelers/|title=Why New York City Is a Major Destination for LGBT Travelers|author=Julia Goicichea|publisher=The Culture Trip|date=August 16, 2017|accessdate=February 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=GayGreenwichVillage2>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/25/nyregion/stonewall-inn-named-national-monument-a-first-for-gay-rights-movement.html\n|title=Stonewall Inn Named National Monument, a First for the Gay Rights Movement|author=Eli Rosenberg|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 24, 2016|accessdate=June 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=GayGreenwichVillage3>{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/diversity/stonewall.htm |title=Workforce Diversity The Stonewall Inn, National Historic Landmark National Register Number: 99000562 |publisher=National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior |accessdate=April 21, 2016}}</ref>\n}} \n{{LGBT sidebar}}\nNew York City has one of the largest [[LGBT culture in New York City|LGBTQ]] populations in the world and the most prominent. Brian Silverman, the author of ''Frommer's New York City from $90 a Day,'' wrote the city has \"one of the world's largest, loudest, and most powerful LGBT communities\", and \"Gay and lesbian culture is as much a part of New York's basic identity as [[yellow cab]]s, high-rises, and [[Broadway theater]]\".<ref>Silverman, Brian. ''Frommer's New York City from $90 a Day'' (Volume 7 of Frommer's $ A Day). [[John Wiley & Sons]], January 21, 2005. {{ISBN|0764588354}}, 9780764588358. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=pZPYLuUnzJ4C&pg=PA28 28].</ref> LGBT Americans in New York City constitute by significant margins the largest self-identifying [[lesbian|'''l'''esbian]], [[gay|'''g'''ay]], [[bisexuality|'''b'''isexual]], and [[transgender|'''t'''ransgender]] communities in the United States, and the 1969 [[Stonewall riots]] in [[Greenwich Village]] are widely considered to be the genesis of the modern [[gay rights]] movement.<ref name=\"StonewallNationalMonument1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/25/nyregion/stonewall-inn-named-national-monument-a-first-for-gay-rights-movement.html|title=Stonewall Inn Named National Monument, a First for the Gay Rights Movement|author=Eli Rosenberg|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 24, 2016|accessdate=September 4, 2016}}</ref> As of 2005, New York City was home to an estimated 272,493 self-identifying gay and bisexual individuals.<ref name=GaryGates>{{cite web |url=http://williamsinstitute.law.ucla.edu/wp-content/uploads/Gates-Same-Sex-Couples-GLB-Pop-ACS-Oct-2006.pdf |title=Same-sex Couples and the Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual Population: New Estimates from the American Community Survey |author=Gary J. Gates |date=October 2006 |publisher=The Williams Institute |accessdate=September 4, 2016}}</ref> The [[New York City metropolitan area]] had an estimated 568,903 self-identifying GLB residents.<ref name=GaryGates/> Meanwhile, New York City is also home to the largest transgender population in the United States, estimated at 50,000 in 2018, concentrated in [[Manhattan]] and [[Queens]].<ref name=NYCTrans>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesledger.com/stories/2016/48/transvigil_2016_11_25_q.html|title=Elmhurst vigil remembers transgender victims lost to violence and hate|author=Bill Parry|newspaper=Daily News|location=New York|date=July 10, 2018|accessdate=November 11, 2018}}</ref> The following represents a list of notable self-identified LGBTQ New Yorkers.\n\n==List of notable self-identified LGBTQ New Yorkers==\n<!---  Please alphabetize correctly and copy-paste the correct hyphen.  --->\n{{Image frame|width=354|content= \u2212 <gallery mode=packed heights=100 style=\"width:350px; background:#fafafa;font-size:85%; line-height:130%;\">\nFile:Acid Betty at RuPaul's Dragcon 2017 by dvsross (2).jpg|[[Acid Betty]]\nFile:Desiree Akhavan 2015-05-24.png|[[Desiree Akhavan]]\nFile:J. Alexander 2014 cropped.jpg|[[J. Alexander (model)|J. Alexander]]\nFile:Michael Alig 2015.jpg|[[Michael Alig]]\nFile:Nahshon_Anderson.jpg|[[Nahshon Dion Anderson]]\nFile:Aquaria, drag queen, 2018.jpg|[[Aquaria (drag queen)|Aquaria]]\nFile:Arden, Michael (2006).jpg|[[Michael Arden]]\nFile:Joey Arias 2009 Howl Festival 1 by DS.jpg|[[Joey Arias]]\nFile:Ellis Avery Author Photo, 2011.jpg|[[Ellis Avery]]\nFile:Fierce Hiro at the Maritime Hotel 20070910.10D.45792 SML (1389640840).jpg|[[Kevin Aviance]]\nFile:Cardi B - Openair Frauenfeld 2019 02.jpg|[[Cardi B]]\nFile:Josh Barro.jpg|[[Josh Barro]]\nFile:James Beard.jpg|[[James Beard]]\nFile:Sandra Bernhard crop.JPG|[[Sandra Bernhard]]\nFile:Mykki Blanco Performing in 2017.jpg|[[Mykki Blanco]]\nFile:Charles blow 2014.jpg|[[Charles Blow]]\nFile:Mal Blum June 2015.JPG|[[Mal Blum]]\nFile:Bob The Drag Queen at Rupaul's Dragcon 2017 by dvsross.jpg|[[Bob The Drag Queen]]\nFile:Matt Bomer Comic-con by Gage Skidmore.jpg|[[Matt Bomer]]\nFile:Keith Boykin 2017.jpg|[[Keith Boykin]]\nFile:Lady Bunny 2001.jpg|[[Lady Bunny]]\nFile:Augusten Burroughs by David Shankbone.jpg|[[Augusten Burroughs]]\nFile:David Burtka 2012.jpg|[[David Burtka]]\nFile:Regie cabico 4192049.JPG|[[Regie Cabico]]\nFile:Rupaul Dragcon 2018-306 (41377493474).jpg|[[Jiggly Caliente]]\nFile:Candis Cayne.jpg|[[Candis Cayne]]\nFile:Cazwell 2015.jpg|[[Cazwell]]\nFile:Andy Cohen at Digitas NewFront 2012 (71