ch |accessdate=April 24, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140823071704/http://hitparade.ch/album/Sonic-Youth/Rather-Ripped-35330 |archivedate=August 23, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Charts UK\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/rather%20ripped/ |title=UK albums charts \u2013 Sonic Youth \u2013 Rather Ripped |website=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=April 24, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019012338/http://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/rather%20ripped/ |archivedate=October 19, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Charts US\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279817/sonic-youth/chart |title=Sonic Youth - Chart history |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=February 25, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127090515/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279817/sonic-youth/chart |archivedate=January 27, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs master|type=album|9938|name=Rather Ripped}}\n\n{{Sonic Youth}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:2006 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by John Agnello]]\n[[Category:Geffen Records albums]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records albums]]\n[[Category:Sonic Youth albums]]\n", "name_user": "Preciouslittle", "label": "safe", "comment": "added link and correct name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rather_Ripped"}
{"title_page": "Miracast", "text_new": "'''Miracast''' is a standard for wireless connections from sending devices (such as laptops, tablets, or smartphones) to display receivers (such as TVs, monitors, or projectors), introduced in 2012 by the [[Wi-Fi Alliance]]. It can roughly be described as \"[[HDMI]] over [[Wi-Fi]]\", replacing the cable from the device to the display.<ref name=\"wifi-democratic-republic\">[https://dvdhrm.wordpress.com/2014/02/17/on-wifi-democratic-republics-and-miracles/ On Wifi-Display, Democratic Republics and Miracles], Patrick Herrmann, on the development of Miraclecast, 2014-02-17.</ref>\n\nThe [[Wi-Fi Alliance]] launched the Miracast certification program at the end of 2012.<ref>https://www.wi-fi.org/news-events/newsroom/wi-fi-alliance-to-launch-wi-fi-certified-miracast-to-deliver-display</ref> Devices that are Miracast-certified can communicate with each other, regardless of manufacturer. Adapters became available that may be plugged either into HDMI or USB ports, allowing devices without built-in Miracast support to connect via Miracast.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} In 2013, [[Nvidia]] announced support for Miracast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/6116/nvidia-announces-compatibility-with-wifi-display-miracast-specification|title=NVIDIA Announces Compatibility with WiFi Display Miracast Specification|date=|publisher=[[AnandTech]]|accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref>\n\nMiracast employs the [[peer-to-peer]] [[Wi-Fi Direct]] standard. It allows sending up to [[1080p]] HD video ([[H.264]] codec) and [[5.1 surround sound]] ([[Advanced Audio Coding|AAC]] and [[Dolby Digital|AC3]] are optional codecs, mandated codec is [[linear pulse-code modulation]]{{snd}}16 bits 48&nbsp;kHz 2 channels).<ref>{{cite web|title=What formats does Miracast support?|url=http://www.wi-fi.org/knowledge-center/faq/what-formats-does-miracast-support|publisher=Wi-fi.org|accessdate=30 October 2015}}</ref> The connection is created via [[Wi-Fi Protected Setup|WPS]] and therefore is secured with [[WPA2]]. IPv4 is used on the [[Internet layer]].  On the transport layer, [[Transmission Control Protocol|TCP]] or [[User Datagram Protocol|UDP]] are used. On the [[application layer]], the stream is initiated and controlled via [[Real Time Streaming Protocol|RTSP]], [[Real-time Transport Protocol|RTP]] for the data transfer.<ref name=\"golem-miracast-2014\">[http://www.golem.de/news/wifi-display-miracast-unter-linux-ist-schrecklich-1402-104315.html \"Miracast unter Linux ist schrecklich\"], golem.de, 2014-02-02.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wi-fi.org/sites/default/files/uploads/wp_Miracast_Industry_20120919.pdf |title=Wi-Fi Certified Miracast : Extending the Wi-Fi experience to seamless video display |publisher=Wi-fi.org |accessdate=2013-10-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209120304/https://www.wi-fi.org/sites/default/files/uploads/wp_Miracast_Industry_20120919.pdf |archivedate=2013-12-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lutz |first=Zachary |url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/07/26/nvidia-throws-support-behind-miracast/ |title=NVIDIA throws support behind Miracast as wireless display standard |publisher=Engadget.com |date=2012-07-26 |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\"arstechnica1\">{{cite web|last=Brodkin |first=Jon |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2012/07/airplay-for-all-miracast-promises-video-streaming-without-the-router/ |title=AirPlay for all? Miracast promises video streaming without the router |publisher=Ars Technica |date=2012-07-10 |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref>\n\n== Devices ==\n\nThe [[Wi-Fi Alliance]] maintains a  list of certified devices, which numbered over 6,700 {{As of|2017|3|9|lc=y}}.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Product finder results |work= Promotional web site |publisher= Wi-Fi Alliance |url= http://www.wi-fi.org/product-finder-results?capabilities=2 |access-date= 9 March 2017 }}</ref>\n\n[[Nvidia]] announced support in 2012 for their [[Tegra&nbsp;3]] platform,<ref>{{cite web|title=Nvidia supports Miracast|url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/07/26/nvidia-throws-support-behind-miracast/}}</ref> and [[Freescale Semiconductor]], [[Texas Instruments]], [[Qualcomm]], [[Marvell Technology Group]] and other chip vendors have also announced their plans to support it.<ref>{{cite web|title=Airplay for all?|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2012/07/airplay-for-all-miracast-promises-video-streaming-without-the-router/}}</ref> Actiontec Electronics also supports Miracast with its line of ScreenBeam products.  <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.screenbeam.com/|title=Wireless Display Solutions {{!}} Miracast {{!}} ScreenBeam|website=ScreenBeam|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-05}}</ref>\n\nBoth devices (the sender and the receiver) need to be Miracast certified for the technology to work. However, to stream music and movies to a non-certified device, Miracast adapters are available that plug into [[HDMI]] or [[Universal Serial Bus|USB]] ports.<ref name=chacos>{{cite news|last=Chacos|first=Brad|title=How Miracast Could Finally Make Your Smartphone Run Your Home Theater|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/how-miracast-could-finally-make-your-smartphone-run-your-home-theater/#ixzz2AnD9bG7X|newspaper=Digital Trends|date=21 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 October 2012, [[Google]] announced that [[Android (operating system)|Android]] version 4.2+ (from updated version of Jelly Bean) are supporting the Miracast wireless display standard, and by default have it integrated.<ref>[http://androidandme.com/2012/10/news/android-4-2-adds-official-support-for-miracast-wireless-display/ Android 4.2 adds official support for Miracast wireless display]</ref> With [[Android Marshmallow|Android 6.0 Marshmallow]], released in 2015, Miracast support was dropped.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs of 8 January 2013, the [[LG]] [[Nexus 4]] and [[Sony]]'s [[Xperia]] Z, ZL, T and V officially supported the function,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phandroid.com/2012/11/19/psa-nexus-7-and-nexus-10-do-not-support-miracast-wireless-display/ |title=PSA: Nexus 7 and Nexus 10 do not support Miracast wireless display |publisher=Phandroid.com |date=2012-11-19 |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.xperiablog.net/2012/12/03/wi-fi-miracast-screen-mirroring-demoed-on-the-xperia-t-video/ |title=Wi-Fi Miracast Screen Mirroring demoed on the Xperia T [Video] |publisher=Xperia Blog |date= |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref> as did [[HTC]] One, [[Motorola]] in their [[Droid Maxx & Ultra]] flagships, and [[Samsung]] in its [[Galaxy S III]] and [[Galaxy Note II]] under the moniker ''AllShare Cast''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tech-recipes.com/rx/51287/how-do-i-mirror-my-samsung-galaxy-phones-screen-on-my-tv/ |title=How Do I Mirror My Samsung Galaxy Phone\u2019s Screen on My TV? |publisher=Tech-Recipes.com |author=Leomar Umpad |date=2014-11-16 |accessdate=2018-10-29}}</ref> The [[Galaxy S4]] uses [[Samsung Link]] for its implementation.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.sammobile.com/2013/03/27/trying-samsungs-renewd-application-samsung-link/ |title=Trying Samsung\u2019s renewed application: Samsung Link |publisher=SamMobile |date=2013-03-27 |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref> \n\nIn October 2013, [[BlackBerry]] released its 10.2.1 update to most of the existing BlackBerry 10 devices available at that time. As of March 2015, the BlackBerry [[BlackBerry Q10|Q10]], [[BlackBerry Q5|Q5]], [[BlackBerry Z30|Z30]], and later models support Miracast streaming; the [[BlackBerry Z10]] does not support Miracast, due to hardware limitations.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://crackberry.com/miracast-will-not-be-available-blackberry-z10|title = Miracast will not be available on the BlackBerry Z10, Wi-Fi Direct supported instead|date = 14 Aug 2013|accessdate = 26 March 2015|website = CrackBerry|publisher = MobileNations|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, [[Rockchip]] unveiled a Miracast adapter powered by the [[RK2928]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnx-software.com/2013/04/14/rockchip-unveils-rk3168-dual-core-processor-showcases-10-miracast-adapter/|title=Rockchip Unveils RK3168 Dual Core Processor, Showcases $10 Miracast Adapter|publisher=Cnx-software.com|accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref>\n\nMicrosoft also added support for Miracast in Windows 8.1 (announced in June 2013) and Windows 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://windowsable.com/set-use-miracast-windows-10/ |title=Miracast for Windows 10 |publisher=Windowsable.com |date= |accessdate=2016-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.windows.com/windows/b/springboard/archive/2013/06/03/what-s-new-for-the-enterprise-in-windows-8-1.aspx |title=What\u2019s New For The Enterprise In Windows 8.1 |publisher=Blogs.windows.com |accessdate=2013-10-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017183211/http://blogs.windows.com/windows/b/springboard/archive/2013/06/03/what-s-new-for-the-enterprise-in-windows-8-1.aspx |archivedate=2013-10-17 }}</ref>  This functionality first became available in the [[Windows 8.1#Windows 8.1|Windows 8.1 Preview]], and is available on hardware with supported Miracast drivers from hardware (GPU) manufacturers such as those listed above.\n\nThe WDTV Live Streaming Media Player added Miracast support with firmware version 2.02.32\n\nThe [[Amazon Fire TV|Amazon Fire TV Stick]], which started shipping on 19 November 2014, also supports Miracast.\n\nThe [[Roku]] streaming stick and Roku TV started providing support for Miracast starting October 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.roku.com/blog/2014/10/02/introducing-roku-screen-mirroring-beta-for-microsoft-windows-and-android-devices|title=Introducing Roku Screen Mirroring Beta for Microsoft\u00ae Windows and Android\u2122 Devices|accessdate=2014-10-02}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 July 2013, Google announced the availability of the [[Chromecast]] powered by a [[Marvell Technology Group|Marvell]] DE3005-A1,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.anandtech.com/show/9688/googles-chromecast-2-is-powered-by-marvells-armada-1500-mini-plus-dual-cortexa7|title=Google\u2019s Chromecast 2 is Powered By Marvell\u2019s ARMADA 1500 Mini Plus - Dual-Core Cortex-A7|last=Smith|first=Ryan|date=|work=Anandtech|access-date=2018-09-06}}</ref> but despite the similarity in name and Google's early support of Miracast in Android, the Chromecast does not support Miracast.\n\nOn 23 September 2014, Microsoft announced the Microsoft Wireless Display Adaptor, a USB-powered HDMI dongle for high definition televisions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=LeBlanc |first1=Brandon |title=Announcing the Microsoft Wireless Display Adapter |url=https://blogs.windows.com/windowsexperience/2014/09/23/announcing-the-microsoft-wireless-display-adapter/ |accessdate=2 March 2020 |work=Windows Experience Blog |publisher=Microsoft Corporation |date=23 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sams |first1=Brad |title=Hands On: Microsoft Wireless Display Adapter |url=https://www.neowin.net/news/hands-on-microsoft-wireless-display-adapter/ |accessdate=2 March 2020 |work=Neowin |date=9 October 2014 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs of late April 2016, the [[Ubuntu Touch]]-powered [[Meizu PRO 5 Ubuntu Edition|Meizu Pro 5]] supported Miracast in OTA-11.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wiki.ubuntu.com/Touch/ReleaseNotes/OTA-11|title=Touch/ReleaseNotes/OTA-11 - Ubuntu Wiki|accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n== Functionality ==\nThe technology was promoted to work across devices, regardless of brand. Miracast devices negotiate settings for each connection, which simplifies the process for the users. In particular, it obviates having to worry about format or [[codec]] details.<ref name=gizmodo>{{cite news|last=Wagner|first=Kyle|title=What Is Miracast?|url=https://gizmodo.com/5944578/what-is-miracast|newspaper=Gizmodo|date=19 September 2012}}</ref> Miracast is \"effectively a wireless [[HDMI cable]], copying everything from one screen to another using the H.264 codec and its own [[digital rights management]] (DRM) layer emulating the HDMI system\". The Wi-Fi Alliance suggested that Miracast could also be used by a [[set-top box]] wanting to [[Streaming media|stream]] content to a TV or tablet.\n\n=== Types of media streamed ===\nMiracast can stream videos that are in [[1080p]], media with DRM such as [[DVD]]s, as well as protected premium content streaming, enabling devices to stream feature films and other copy-protected materials. This is accomplished by using a Wi-Fi version of the same trusted content mechanisms used on cable-based HDMI and [[DisplayPort]] connections.<ref name=kevin>{{cite news|last=Parrish|first=Kevin|title=Wi-Fi Alliance Announces First Miracast-Certified Devices|url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/Wi-Fi-Direct-Miracast-Wi-Fi-Alliance-WiDi-HDMI,17746.html|newspaper=Tom's Hardware|date=19 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==== Display resolution ====\n\n* 27 Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) formats, from 640 x 480 up to 4096 x 2160 pixels, and from 24 to 60 frames per second (fps)\n* 34 Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) formats, from 800 x 600 up to 2560 x 1600 pixels, and from 30 to 60 fps\n* 12 handheld formats, from 640 x 360 up to 960 x 540 pixels, and from 30 to 60 fps\n* Mandatory: 1280 x 720p30 (HD)\n* Optional: 3840 x 2160p60 (4K Ultra HD)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wi-fi.org/download.php?file=/sites/default/files/private/Wi-Fi%20CERTIFIED%20Miracast%20Technical%20Overview_20170725.pdf|title=certification url check {{!}} Wi-Fi Alliance|website=www.wi-fi.org|language=en|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==== Video ====\nMandatory: ITU-T H.264 (Advanced Video Coding [AVC]) for HD and Ultra HD video; supports several profiles in transcoding and non-transcoding modes, including Constrained Baseline Profile (CBP), at levels ranging from 3.1 to 5.2 \n\nOptional: ITU-T H.265 (High Efficiency Video Coding [HEVC]) for HD and Ultra HD video; supports several profiles in transcoding and non-transcoding modes, including Main Profile, Main 444, SCC-8 bit 444, Main 444 10, at levels ranging from 3.1 to 5.1\n\n==== Audio ====\nMandated audio codec: Linear Pulse-Code Modulation (LPCM) 16 bits, 48 kHz sampling, 2 channels\n\nOptional audio codecs, including:\n\n* LPCM mode 16 bits, 44.1 kHz sampling, 2 channels\n* Advanced Audio Coding (AAC) modes\n* Dolby Advanced Codec 3 (AC3) modes\n* E-AC-3\n* Dolby TrueHD, Dolby MAT modes\n* DTS-HD mode\n* MPEG-4 AAC and MPEG-H 3D Audio modes\n* AAC-ELDv2\n\n== Version history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Version\n!Date\n!Remarks<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wi-fi.org/download.php?file=/sites/default/files/private/Wi-Fi_Display_Technical_Specification_v2.1_0.pdf|title=certification url check {{!}} Wi-Fi Alliance|website=www.wi-fi.org|language=en|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|1.0\n|24-08-2012\n|Public release version\n|-\n|1.1\n|24-04-2014\n|Public release for HDCPv2.2 updates.\n|-\n|2.0\n|21-04-2017\n|Release 2 final version.\n|-\n|2.1\n|31-07-2017\n|Corrected heading errors in sections 4.3 and 4.4.\nRemoved references to Miracast.\n|}\n\n== Issues ==\nCertification does not mandate a maximum latency (i.e. the time between display of picture on the source and display of the mirrored image on the sync display).\n\nAlthough trumpeted as a major feature of Android Kit Kat, support in Android was dropped in 2015, and ''[[Computerworld]]'' observed that \"Miracast never quite caught on as a standard\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.computerworld.com/article/3239864/android/android-nostalgia-old-features.html|title=Android nostalgia: 13 once-trumpeted features that quietly faded away|last=Raphael|first=JR|date=2017-12-05|work=Computerworld|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== OS support ==\n=== Windows ===\nThe latest [[Windows 10]] release supports Miracast receiving along with User Input Back Channel (UIBC) support to allow for [[human interface devices]] (touch screens, mouse, keyboard) to also have wireless connectivity (provided the host hardware also supports this). [[Windows 8.1]] supports broadcasting/sending the screen via Miracast. Miracast is also built into [[Windows Phone 8.1]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.windows.com/windows/b/windowsexperience/archive/2013/11/12/windows-8-1-on-your-big-screen-with-miracast.aspx |publisher=blogs.microsoft.com |title=Windows 8.1 on your big screen with Miracast |date=2013-11-12 |accessdate=2013-11-12}}</ref> Developers can also implement Miracast on top of the built-in [[Wi-Fi Direct]] support in [[Windows 7]] and [[Windows 8]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/hardware/jj124675.aspx |title=DMR support for Wi-Fi Direct (WFD-01) |publisher=Msdn.microsoft.com |date=2013-07-26 |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref> Another way to support Miracast in Windows is with Intel's proprietary [[WiDi]] (v3.5 or higher). A software-based Miracast receiver for Windows 8.1, AirServer Universal, was made available on 31 October 2014 by App Dynamic.<ref>http://airserver.com/history</ref>\n\n=== iOS and macOS ===\nApple does not support the Miracast standard on [[iOS]] or [[macOS]], instead using its own [[proprietary protocol|proprietary]] peer-to-peer [[AirPlay]] protocol.\n\n=== Linux desktop ===\nMiracleCast<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/albfan/miraclecast|title=Miraclecast|website=miraclecast GitHub}}</ref> provides early support for Miracast, but is not tied to that single protocol.\n\nWireless Display Software for Linux OS (WDS)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://01.org/wds|title=WDS|website=WDS}}</ref> initial Miracast support, developed by Intel.\n\n=== Android ===\nGoogle does not support the Miracast standard on Android. Miracast support had been built into [[Android (operating system)|Android]] with version 4.2<ref>{{cite web|url=http://howto.cnet.com/8301-11310_39-57604270-285/miracast-everything-to-know-about-mirroring-android |publisher=CNET |title=Miracast: Everything to know about mirroring Android |date=2013-09-24 |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> and starting with Android 4.4, devices could be certified to the Wi-Fi Alliance Display Specification as Miracast compatible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://developer.android.com/about/versions/kitkat.html |title=Android Kitkat Overview |publisher=developer.android.com |date=2013-10-31 |accessdate=2013-11-12}}</ref>, but support was dropped with [[Android Marshmallow|Android 6.0 Marshmallow]] in 2015 in favor of Google's own proprietary [[Google Cast]] protocol.<ref name=\":0\" /> Some manufacturers of Android devices step in and support Miracast through their software.<ref>See, for example, [https://www.htc.com/us/support/apps/htc-connect/ HTC Connect].</ref> While Miracast is also used on Android Smart TV<ref>{{cite web|url= https://letsview.com/android-tv |title= Miracast built-in Android TV | publisher=LetsView}}</ref> as a built-in feature.\n\n=== BlackBerry OS ===\nMiracast is also supported by [[BlackBerry 10|BlackBerry OS]] from version 10.2.1 onwards.\n\n== See also ==\n\n\n* [[AirPlay]]\n* [[Discovery and Launch]] (Used by Netflix app)\n* [[Digital Living Network Alliance|DLNA (Digital Living Network Alliance)]]\n* [[WiDi]]\n* [[Google Cast]]\n* [[Smart Display]] (Codename Mira, early 2002s screen casting by Microsoft)\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.wi-fi.org/file/wi-fi-certified-miracast%E2%84%A2-extending-the-wi-fi-experience-to-seamless-video-display-industry |title= Wi-Fi Certified Miracast: Extending the Wi-Fi experience to seamless video display - Industry |date= 2012 |format= pdf |website= [[Wi-Fi Alliance]] |access-date= 2014-05-01 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140502004434/http://www.wi-fi.org/file/wi-fi-certified-miracast%E2%84%A2-extending-the-wi-fi-experience-to-seamless-video-display-industry |archive-date= 2014-05-02 |url-status= dead }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.portablehifi.com/wireless-hdmi-transmission-protocols-products |title= The Main Wireless HDMI Transmission Protocols and Their Typical Products |website= Portable Hi-Fi |date= 2014 }}\n\n\n[[Category:Internet Standards]]\n[[Category:Wi-Fi]]\n[[Category:Wi-Fi Direct]]\n[[Category:Wireless display technologies]]\n", "text_old": "'''Miracast''' is a standard for wireless connections from sending devices (such as laptops, tablets, or smartphones) to display receivers (such as TVs, monitors, or projectors), introduced in 2012 by the [[Wi-Fi Alliance]]. It can roughly be described as \"[[HDMI]] over [[Wi-Fi]]\", replacing the cable from the device to the display.<ref name=\"wifi-democratic-republic\">[https://dvdhrm.wordpress.com/2014/02/17/on-wifi-democratic-republics-and-miracles/ On Wifi-Display, Democratic Republics and Miracles], Patrick Herrmann, on the development of Miraclecast, 2014-02-17.</ref>\n\nThe [[Wi-Fi Alliance]] launched the Miracast certification program at the end of 2012.<ref>https://www.wi-fi.org/news-events/newsroom/wi-fi-alliance-to-launch-wi-fi-certified-miracast-to-deliver-display</ref> Devices that are Miracast-certified can communicate with each other, regardless of manufacturer. Adapters became available that may be plugged either into HDMI or USB ports, allowing devices without built-in Miracast support to connect via Miracast.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} In 2013, [[Nvidia]] announced support for Miracast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/6116/nvidia-announces-compatibility-with-wifi-display-miracast-specification|title=NVIDIA Announces Compatibility with WiFi Display Miracast Specification|date=|publisher=[[AnandTech]]|accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref>\n\nMiracast employs the [[peer-to-peer]] [[Wi-Fi Direct]] standard. It allows sending up to [[1080p]] HD video ([[H.264]] codec) and [[5.1 surround sound]] ([[Advanced Audio Coding|AAC]] and [[Dolby Digital|AC3]] are optional codecs, mandated codec is [[linear pulse-code modulation]]{{snd}}16 bits 48&nbsp;kHz 2 channels).<ref>{{cite web|title=What formats does Miracast support?|url=http://www.wi-fi.org/knowledge-center/faq/what-formats-does-miracast-support|publisher=Wi-fi.org|accessdate=30 October 2015}}</ref> The connection is created via [[Wi-Fi Protected Setup|WPS]] and therefore is secured with [[WPA2]]. IPv4 is used on the [[Internet layer]].  On the transport layer, [[Transmission Control Protocol|TCP]] or [[User Datagram Protocol|UDP]] are used. On the [[application layer]], the stream is initiated and controlled via [[Real Time Streaming Protocol|RTSP]], [[Real-time Transport Protocol|RTP]] for the data transfer.<ref name=\"golem-miracast-2014\">[http://www.golem.de/news/wifi-display-miracast-unter-linux-ist-schrecklich-1402-104315.html \"Miracast unter Linux ist schrecklich\"], golem.de, 2014-02-02.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wi-fi.org/sites/default/files/uploads/wp_Miracast_Industry_20120919.pdf |title=Wi-Fi Certified Miracast : Extending the Wi-Fi experience to seamless video display |publisher=Wi-fi.org |accessdate=2013-10-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209120304/https://www.wi-fi.org/sites/default/files/uploads/wp_Miracast_Industry_20120919.pdf |archivedate=2013-12-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lutz |first=Zachary |url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/07/26/nvidia-throws-support-behind-miracast/ |title=NVIDIA throws support behind Miracast as wireless display standard |publisher=Engadget.com |date=2012-07-26 |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\"arstechnica1\">{{cite web|last=Brodkin |first=Jon |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2012/07/airplay-for-all-miracast-promises-video-streaming-without-the-router/ |title=AirPlay for all? Miracast promises video streaming without the router |publisher=Ars Technica |date=2012-07-10 |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref>\n\n== Devices ==\n\nThe [[Wi-Fi Alliance]] maintains a  list of certified devices, which numbered over 6,700 {{As of|2017|3|9|lc=y}}.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Product finder results |work= Promotional web site |publisher= Wi-Fi Alliance |url= http://www.wi-fi.org/product-finder-results?capabilities=2 |access-date= 9 March 2017 }}</ref>\n\n[[Nvidia]] announced support in 2012 for their [[Tegra&nbsp;3]] platform,<ref>{{cite web|title=Nvidia supports Miracast|url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/07/26/nvidia-throws-support-behind-miracast/}}</ref> and [[Freescale Semiconductor]], [[Texas Instruments]], [[Qualcomm]], [[Marvell Technology Group]] and other chip vendors have also announced their plans to support it.<ref>{{cite web|title=Airplay for all?|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2012/07/airplay-for-all-miracast-promises-video-streaming-without-the-router/}}</ref> Actiontec Electronics also supports Miracast with its line of ScreenBeam products.  <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.screenbeam.com/|title=Wireless Display Solutions {{!}} Miracast {{!}} ScreenBeam|website=ScreenBeam|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-05}}</ref>\n\nBoth devices (the sender and the receiver) need to be Miracast certified for the technology to work. However, to stream music and movies to a non-certified device, Miracast adapters are available that plug into [[HDMI]] or [[Universal Serial Bus|USB]] ports.<ref name=chacos>{{cite news|last=Chacos|first=Brad|title=How Miracast Could Finally Make Your Smartphone Run Your Home Theater|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/how-miracast-could-finally-make-your-smartphone-run-your-home-theater/#ixzz2AnD9bG7X|newspaper=Digital Trends|date=21 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 October 2012, [[Google]] announced that [[Android (operating system)|Android]] version 4.2+ (from updated version of Jelly Bean) are supporting the Miracast wireless display standard, and by default have it integrated.<ref>[http://androidandme.com/2012/10/news/android-4-2-adds-official-support-for-miracast-wireless-display/ Android 4.2 adds official support for Miracast wireless display]</ref> With [[Android Marshmallow|Android 6.0 Marshmallow]], released in 2015, Miracast support was dropped.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs of 8 January 2013, the [[LG]] [[Nexus 4]] and [[Sony]]'s [[Xperia]] Z, ZL, T and V officially supported the function,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phandroid.com/2012/11/19/psa-nexus-7-and-nexus-10-do-not-support-miracast-wireless-display/ |title=PSA: Nexus 7 and Nexus 10 do not support Miracast wireless display |publisher=Phandroid.com |date=2012-11-19 |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.xperiablog.net/2012/12/03/wi-fi-miracast-screen-mirroring-demoed-on-the-xperia-t-video/ |title=Wi-Fi Miracast Screen Mirroring demoed on the Xperia T [Video] |publisher=Xperia Blog |date= |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref> as did [[HTC]] One, [[Motorola]] in their [[Droid Maxx & Ultra]] flagships, and [[Samsung]] in its [[Galaxy S III]] and [[Galaxy Note II]] under the moniker ''AllShare Cast''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tech-recipes.com/rx/51287/how-do-i-mirror-my-samsung-galaxy-phones-screen-on-my-tv/ |title=How Do I Mirror My Samsung Galaxy Phone\u2019s Screen on My TV? |publisher=Tech-Recipes.com |author=Leomar Umpad |date=2014-11-16 |accessdate=2018-10-29}}</ref> The [[Galaxy S4]] uses [[Samsung Link]] for its implementation.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.sammobile.com/2013/03/27/trying-samsungs-renewd-application-samsung-link/ |title=Trying Samsung\u2019s renewed application: Samsung Link |publisher=SamMobile |date=2013-03-27 |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref> \n\nIn October 2013, [[BlackBerry]] released its 10.2.1 update to most of the existing BlackBerry 10 devices available at that time. As of March 2015, the BlackBerry [[BlackBerry Q10|Q10]], [[BlackBerry Q5|Q5]], [[BlackBerry Z30|Z30]], and later models support Miracast streaming; the [[BlackBerry Z10]] does not support Miracast, due to hardware limitations.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://crackberry.com/miracast-will-not-be-available-blackberry-z10|title = Miracast will not be available on the BlackBerry Z10, Wi-Fi Direct supported instead|date = 14 Aug 2013|accessdate = 26 March 2015|website = CrackBerry|publisher = MobileNations|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, [[Rockchip]] unveiled a Miracast adapter powered by the [[RK2928]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnx-software.com/2013/04/14/rockchip-unveils-rk3168-dual-core-processor-showcases-10-miracast-adapter/|title=Rockchip Unveils RK3168 Dual Core Processor, Showcases $10 Miracast Adapter|publisher=Cnx-software.com|accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref>\n\nMicrosoft also added support for Miracast in Windows 8.1 (announced in June 2013) and Windows 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://windowsable.com/set-use-miracast-windows-10/ |title=Miracast for Windows 10 |publisher=Windowsable.com |date= |accessdate=2016-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.windows.com/windows/b/springboard/archive/2013/06/03/what-s-new-for-the-enterprise-in-windows-8-1.aspx |title=What\u2019s New For The Enterprise In Windows 8.1 |publisher=Blogs.windows.com |accessdate=2013-10-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017183211/http://blogs.windows.com/windows/b/springboard/archive/2013/06/03/what-s-new-for-the-enterprise-in-windows-8-1.aspx |archivedate=2013-10-17 }}</ref>  This functionality first became available in the [[Windows 8.1#Windows 8.1|Windows 8.1 Preview]], and is available on hardware with supported Miracast drivers from hardware (GPU) manufacturers such as those listed above.\n\nThe WDTV Live Streaming Media Player added Miracast support with firmware version 2.02.32\n\nThe [[Amazon Fire TV|Amazon Fire TV Stick]], which started shipping on 19 November 2014, also supports Miracast.\n\nThe [[Roku]] streaming stick and Roku TV started providing support for Miracast starting October 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.roku.com/blog/2014/10/02/introducing-roku-screen-mirroring-beta-for-microsoft-windows-and-android-devices|title=Introducing Roku Screen Mirroring Beta for Microsoft\u00ae Windows and Android\u2122 Devices|accessdate=2014-10-02}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 July 2013, Google announced the availability of the [[Chromecast]] powered by a [[Marvell Technology Group|Marvell]] DE3005-A1,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.anandtech.com/show/9688/googles-chromecast-2-is-powered-by-marvells-armada-1500-mini-plus-dual-cortexa7|title=Google\u2019s Chromecast 2 is Powered By Marvell\u2019s ARMADA 1500 Mini Plus - Dual-Core Cortex-A7|last=Smith|first=Ryan|date=|work=Anandtech|access-date=2018-09-06}}</ref> but despite the similarity in name and Google's early support of Miracast in Android, the Chromecast does not support Miracast.\n\nOn 23 September 2014, Microsoft announced the Microsoft Wireless Display Adaptor, a USB-powered HDMI dongle for high definition televisions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=LeBlanc |first1=Brandon |title=Announcing the Microsoft Wireless Display Adapter |url=https://blogs.windows.com/windowsexperience/2014/09/23/announcing-the-microsoft-wireless-display-adapter/ |accessdate=2 March 2020 |work=Windows Experience Blog |publisher=Microsoft Corporation |date=23 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sams |first1=Brad |title=Hands On: Microsoft Wireless Display Adapter |url=https://www.neowin.net/news/hands-on-microsoft-wireless-display-adapter/ |accessdate=2 March 2020 |work=Neowin |date=9 October 2014 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs of late April 2016, the [[Ubuntu Touch]]-powered [[Meizu PRO 5 Ubuntu Edition|Meizu Pro 5]] supported Miracast in OTA-11.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wiki.ubuntu.com/Touch/ReleaseNotes/OTA-11|title=Touch/ReleaseNotes/OTA-11 - Ubuntu Wiki|accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n== Functionality ==\nThe technology was promoted to work across devices, regardless of brand. Miracast devices negotiate settings for each connection, which simplifies the process for the users. In particular, it obviates having to worry about format or [[codec]] details.<ref name=gizmodo>{{cite news|last=Wagner|first=Kyle|title=What Is Miracast?|url=https://gizmodo.com/5944578/what-is-miracast|newspaper=Gizmodo|date=19 September 2012}}</ref> Miracast is \"effectively a wireless [[HDMI cable]], copying everything from one screen to another using the H.264 codec and its own [[digital rights management]] (DRM) layer emulating the HDMI system\". The Wi-Fi Alliance suggested that Miracast could also be used by a [[set-top box]] wanting to [[Streaming media|stream]] content to a TV or tablet.\n\n=== Types of media streamed ===\nMiracast can stream videos that are in [[1080p]], media with DRM such as [[DVD]]s, as well as protected premium content streaming, enabling devices to stream feature films and other copy-protected materials. This is accomplished by using a Wi-Fi version of the same trusted content mechanisms used on cable-based HDMI and [[DisplayPort]] connections.<ref name=kevin>{{cite news|last=Parrish|first=Kevin|title=Wi-Fi Alliance Announces First Miracast-Certified Devices|url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/Wi-Fi-Direct-Miracast-Wi-Fi-Alliance-WiDi-HDMI,17746.html|newspaper=Tom's Hardware|date=19 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==== Display resolution ====\n\n* 27 Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) formats, from 640 x 480 up to 4096 x 2160 pixels, and from 24 to 60 frames per second (fps)\n* 34 Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) formats, from 800 x 600 up to 2560 x 1600 pixels, and from 30 to 60 fps\n* 12 handheld formats, from 640 x 360 up to 960 x 540 pixels, and from 30 to 60 fps\n* Mandatory: 1280 x 720p30 (HD)\n* Optional: 3840 x 2160p60 (4K Ultra HD)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wi-fi.org/download.php?file=/sites/default/files/private/Wi-Fi%20CERTIFIED%20Miracast%20Technical%20Overview_20170725.pdf|title=certification url check {{!}} Wi-Fi Alliance|website=www.wi-fi.org|language=en|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==== Video ====\nMandatory: ITU-T H.264 (Advanced Video Coding [AVC]) for HD and Ultra HD video; supports several profiles in transcoding and non-transcoding modes, including Constrained Baseline Profile (CBP), at levels ranging from 3.1 to 5.2 \n\nOptional: ITU-T H.265 (High Efficiency Video Coding [HEVC]) for HD and Ultra HD video; supports several profiles in transcoding and non-transcoding modes, including Main Profile, Main 444, SCC-8 bit 444, Main 444 10, at levels ranging from 3.1 to 5.1\n\n==== Audio ====\nMandated audio codec: Linear Pulse-Code Modulation (LPCM) 16 bits, 48 kHz sampling, 2 channels\n\nOptional audio codecs, including:\n\n* LPCM mode 16 bits, 44.1 kHz sampling, 2 channels\n* Advanced Audio Coding (AAC) modes\n* Dolby Advanced Codec 3 (AC3) modes\n* E-AC-3\n* Dolby TrueHD, Dolby MAT modes\n* DTS-HD mode\n* MPEG-4 AAC and MPEG-H 3D Audio modes\n* AAC-ELDv2\n\n== Version history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Version\n!Date\n!Remarks<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wi-fi.org/download.php?file=/sites/default/files/private/Wi-Fi_Display_Technical_Specification_v2.1_0.pdf|title=certification url check {{!}} Wi-Fi Alliance|website=www.wi-fi.org|language=en|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|1.0\n|24-08-2012\n|Public release version\n|-\n|1.1\n|24-04-2014\n|Public release for HDCPv2.2 updates.\n|-\n|2.0\n|21-04-2017\n|Release 2 final version.\n|-\n|2.1\n|31-07-2017\n|Corrected heading errors in sections 4.3 and 4.4.\nRemoved references to Miracast.\n|}\n\n== Issues ==\nCertification does not mandate a maximum latency (i.e. the time between display of picture on the source and display of the mirrored image on the sync display).\n\nAlthough trumpeted as a major feature of Android Kit Kat, support in Android was dropped in 2015, and ''[[Computerworld]]'' observed that \"Miracast never quite caught on as a standard\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.computerworld.com/article/3239864/android/android-nostalgia-old-features.html|title=Android nostalgia: 13 once-trumpeted features that quietly faded away|last=Raphael|first=JR|date=2017-12-05|work=Computerworld|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== OS support ==\n=== Windows ===\nThe latest [[Windows 10]] release supports Miracast receiving along with User Input Back Channel (UIBC) support to allow for [[human interface devices]] (touch screens, mouse, keyboard) to also have wireless connectivity (provided the host hardware also supports this). [[Windows 8.1]] supports broadcasting/sending the screen via Miracast. Miracast is also built into [[Windows Phone 8.1]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.windows.com/windows/b/windowsexperience/archive/2013/11/12/windows-8-1-on-your-big-screen-with-miracast.aspx |publisher=blogs.microsoft.com |title=Windows 8.1 on your big screen with Miracast |date=2013-11-12 |accessdate=2013-11-12}}</ref> Developers can also implement Miracast on top of the built-in [[Wi-Fi Direct]] support in [[Windows 7]] and [[Windows 8]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/hardware/jj124675.aspx |title=DMR support for Wi-Fi Direct (WFD-01) |publisher=Msdn.microsoft.com |date=2013-07-26 |accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref> Another way to support Miracast in Windows is with Intel's proprietary [[WiDi]] (v3.5 or higher). A software-based Miracast receiver for Windows 8.1, AirServer Universal, was made available on 31 October 2014 by App Dynamic.<ref>http://airserver.com/history</ref>\n\n=== iOS and macOS ===\nApple does not support the Miracast standard on [[iOS]] or [[macOS]], instead using its own [[proprietary protocol|proprietary]] peer-to-peer [[AirPlay]] protocol.\n\n=== Linux desktop ===\nMiracleCast<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/albfan/miraclecast|title=Miraclecast|website=miraclecast GitHub}}</ref> provides early support for Miracast, but is not tied to that single protocol.\n\nWireless Display Software for Linux OS (WDS)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://01.org/wds|title=WDS|website=WDS}}</ref> initial Miracast support, developed by Intel.\n\n=== Android ===\nGoogle does not support the Miracast standard on Android. Miracast support had been built into [[Android (operating system)|Android]] with version 4.2<ref>{{cite web|url=http://howto.cnet.com/8301-11310_39-57604270-285/miracast-everything-to-know-about-mirroring-android |publisher=CNET |title=Miracast: Everything to know about mirroring Android |date=2013-09-24 |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> and starting with Android 4.4, devices could be certified to the Wi-Fi Alliance Display Specification as Miracast compatible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://developer.android.com/about/versions/kitkat.html |title=Android Kitkat Overview |publisher=developer.android.com |date=2013-10-31 |accessdate=2013-11-12}}</ref>, but support was dropped with [[Android Marshmallow|Android 6.0 Marshmallow]] in 2015 in favor of Google's own proprietary [[Google Cast]] protocol.<ref name=\":0\" /> Some manufacturers of Android devices step in and support Miracast through their software.<ref>See, for example, [https://www.htc.com/us/support/apps/htc-connect/ HTC Connect].</ref>\n\n=== BlackBerry OS ===\nMiracast is also supported by [[BlackBerry 10|BlackBerry OS]] from version 10.2.1 onwards.\n\n== See also ==\n\n\n* [[AirPlay]]\n* [[Discovery and Launch]] (Used by Netflix app)\n* [[Digital Living Network Alliance|DLNA (Digital Living Network Alliance)]]\n* [[WiDi]]\n* [[Google Cast]]\n* [[Smart Display]] (Codename Mira, early 2002s screen casting by Microsoft)\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.wi-fi.org/file/wi-fi-certified-miracast%E2%84%A2-extending-the-wi-fi-experience-to-seamless-video-display-industry |title= Wi-Fi Certified Miracast: Extending the Wi-Fi experience to seamless video display - Industry |date= 2012 |format= pdf |website= [[Wi-Fi Alliance]] |access-date= 2014-05-01 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140502004434/http://www.wi-fi.org/file/wi-fi-certified-miracast%E2%84%A2-extending-the-wi-fi-experience-to-seamless-video-display-industry |archive-date= 2014-05-02 |url-status= dead }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.portablehifi.com/wireless-hdmi-transmission-protocols-products |title= The Main Wireless HDMI Transmission Protocols and Their Typical Products |website= Portable Hi-Fi |date= 2014 }}\n\n\n[[Category:Internet Standards]]\n[[Category:Wi-Fi]]\n[[Category:Wi-Fi Direct]]\n[[Category:Wireless display technologies]]\n", "name_user": "GregoryWatt", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAndroid)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miracast"}
